      "prediction_raw": "To walk without using any door more than once, the walk must be a closed trail in the grid graph.\n\nThe 11 × 11 grid has  \n\n* Vertices (cells): \\(11\\cdot 11 = 121\\)  \n* Edges (doors): horizontal \\(11\\cdot 10 = 110\\) plus vertical \\(10\\cdot 11 = 110\\); total \\(220\\).\n\nA closed trail can use an edge at most once, so the set of used edges must form a subgraph in which every vertex has **even** degree (otherwise the trail could not start and finish at the same vertex).  \n\nIn the full grid the degrees are:\n\n* interior cells – degree 4 (even)  \n* corner cells – degree 2 (even)  \n* non‑corner boundary cells – degree 3 (odd)\n\nThe non‑corner boundary cells are the only odd‑degree vertices.  \nEach side of the 11 × 11 grid has \\(11-2 = 9\\) such cells, so there are  \n\n\\[\n4\\cdot 9 = 36\n\\]\n\nodd‑degree vertices.\n\nTo make all degrees even we must delete some edges. Deleting one edge flips the parity of its two endpoints, so each deleted edge can “fix’’ at most two odd vertices. Consequently at least  \n\n\\[\n\\frac{36}{2}=18\n\\]\n\nedges must be omitted.\n\nThus the number of doors that can be traversed is at most  \n\n\\[\n220-18 = 202.\n\\]\n\nIt is possible to achieve this bound: pair the 36 odd vertices with 18 disjoint edges along the perimeter (pair adjacent odd cells on each side, and pair the four remaining odd vertices with interior edges). Removing exactly those 18 edges leaves every vertex with even degree, giving an Eulerian subgraph containing 202 edges, and an Eulerian circuit (a closed trail) that uses all of them.\n\nHence the maximal number of doors Karthik can go through is **202**.\n\n**The answer is 202**",
